snippet: Voters will cast ballots for the second time in two months, worried that any government they elect will fail to resolve the political and economic turmoil that threatens Greece’s future.
abstract: Greek voters prepare to head to the polls for the second time in two months, attended by a sense of dread that any government that comes to power will fail to resolve the political and economic turmoil that threatens the country’s future; victorious party will face an uphill battle to inject confidence into a paralyzed economy that depends heavily on the continued infusion of money by the European Central Bank.

byline.original: By RACHEL DONADIO and STEVEN ERLANGER
byline.contributor: Rachel Donadio reported from Athens, and Steven Erlanger from Paris. Jack Ewing contributed reporting from Frankfurt.

lead_paragraph: Voters will cast ballots for the second time in two months, worried that any government they elect will fail to resolve the political and economic turmoil that threatens Greece’s future.

headline.seo: In Greece, Fears That Voting Won’t Resolve Turmoil
headline.main: As Greeks Head to Polls Again, a Fear That No One Will Win
headline.print_headline: In Greek Vote, Fears Nobody Can Truly Win
